    <h1><span  style="font-family: Calibri;">Add object to the scene</span></h1>
    <span  style="font-family: Calibri;">To project a 3D model on your detected
      real object, you can access the <span  style="font-weight: bold;">File
        &gt; Add object to the scene</span> options dialog in the menu bar.<br>
      <br>
    </span>
    <div  style="text-align: center;"><span  style="font-family: Calibri;"><img
           title="addobject"  alt="Add object dialog"  src="file:///C:/Users/Leo/Dropbox/ProjetM2/HowTo/images/addobject.png"><br>
      </span>
      <div  style="text-align: left;">
        <ul  style="text-align: justify;">
          <li><span  style="font-weight: bold;"><span  style="color: rgb(41, 128, 185);"><span
                   style="font-family: Calibri;">Box 1 : </span></span></span><span
               style="color: rgb(41, 128, 185);"><span  style="font-family: Calibri;"><span
                   style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">You may chose the fast way to
                  add objects to the scene, by using automatic templates
                  integrated in the software. The first and third one are
                  related to <strong>Face detection</strong>, whereas the
                  second one in optimized for a <strong>Board detection</strong>.
                  Finally, the last icon will project a 3D landmark in order to
                  display axis in the scene.</span></span></span></li>
        </ul>
        <ul  style="text-align: justify;">
          <li><span  style="font-weight: bold;"><span  style="color: rgb(46, 204, 113);"><span
                   style="font-family: Calibri;">Box 2 : </span></span></span><span
               style="color: rgb(46, 204, 113);"><span  style="font-family: Calibri;"><span
                   style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">If you prefer to add a single
                  personal object, you may select the correct <strong>Loading
                    path</strong> and specify a <strong>Name </strong>to help
                  you set its properties after that. If you also wish to add a
                  texture for this object, a <strong>Texture path</strong> is
                  available.</span></span></span></li>
        </ul>
        <div  style="text-align: justify;"><span  style=" color: rgb(46, 204, 113);"><span
               style=" font-family: Calibri;"><span  style=" color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Note
                that you have the possibility to <strong>delete</strong> and/or
                <strong>display</strong> a specific and/or all objects with the
                general toolbar. If you wish to try augmented reality on a video
                of your own, you may select its path with the <strong>Video
                  Input </strong>menu.<br>
                <br>
              </span></span></span>
          <div  style="text-align: center;"><span  style="color: rgb(46, 204, 113); font-style: italic;"><span
                 style=" font-family: Calibri;"><span  style=" color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Thanks
                  for using this software, do not fear to experiment and have
                  fun!<br>
                  <br>
